  "paper_analysis": {
    "summary": "This paper studies ultra-clean PdCoO2, a quasi-2D delafossite metal with a strongly faceted in-plane Fermi surface, using focused-ion-beam-micromachined transport bars cut at different angles to the crystal axes. The key finding is that when the channel width becomes smaller than the electron mean free path, transport becomes direction-dependent: the apparent resistivity can vary by more than a factor of two and a zero-field transverse voltage appears, both explained by directional ballistic boundary scattering and reproduced by simulations.",
